lemma initial_both_or_neither (S : List (Call m)) :
    ∀c ∈ S, (isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c)
    ∨ ¬(isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c) := by
  by_contra hyp
  -- We assume that there exists a c in S such that neither (P ∧ Q) nor ¬(P ∧ Q) holds
  have h₁ : ∃ (c : Call m), c ∈ S ∧ ¬((isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c) ∨ ¬(isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c)) := by
    -- Use the assumption to get such a c
    have h₂ := hyp
    simp only [not_forall, not_or] at h₂
    obtain ⟨c, hc, h₃⟩ := h₂
    exact ⟨c, hc, h₃⟩
  -- Obtain such a c
  obtain ⟨c, hc, h₃⟩ := h₁
  -- This leads to a contradiction because (P ∧ Q) ∨ ¬(P ∧ Q) is always true
  have h₄ : (isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c) ∨ ¬(isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c) := by
    by_cases h₅ : isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c
    · exact Or.inl h₅
    · exact Or.inr h₅
  -- Contradiction arises as we assumed the negation of this
  exact h₃ h₄
``` 

This proof works as follows:
1. Assume the statement is false, i.e., there exists some `c ∈ S` such that neither the conjunction nor its negation holds.
2. Use classical logic to derive that either the conjunction holds or its negation holds (`h₄`).
3. This directly contradicts the assumption (`h₃`). 

But actually, this is even simpler: we can prove that for any `c`, `(isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c) ∨ ¬(isAgentInitialCall S c.fst c ∧ isAgentInitialCall S c.snd c)` holds by classical logic, so assuming that it does not leads immediately to `False`. 

